  <question type="stack">
    <name>
      <text>Conversion of Complex Number: Cartesian to Polar and Exponential Forms</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Consider the complex number \(z = {@aa@} {@sigb@} {@ev(abs(bb),simp)@}\cdot i\).</p>
<p>1. Write \(z\) in polar or trigonometric form. Give the modulus in exact form and the argument correct to \(2\) decimal places within your answer.</p>
<p>\(z = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>
<p>2. Write \(z\) in exponential form. Give the modulus and the argument in exact form. Recall that \(e^k\) is entered as <code>%e^(k)</code>.</p>
<p>\(z = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution:</h3>
<p>1. To write \(z\) in polar form, we need to find its modulus and argument.</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle r = |z| = \sqrt{{@lba@}{@aa@}{@rba@}^2 + {@lbb@}{@bb@}{@rbb@}^2}\)</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle  = \sqrt{{@aa^2+bb^2@}}\)</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle  = {@mod@}\).</p>
<p>To find the argument, we find the argument of \(\displaystyle {@ev(abs(aa),simp)@} + {@ev(abs(bb),simp)@}\cdot i\), which is</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle \tan^{-1} \left( \frac{{@ev(abs(bb),simp)@}}{{@ev(abs(aa),simp)@}} \right) = {@dispdp(primarg,2)@}\)</p>
<p>If not in the first quadrant, we need to use the symmetry in the Argand Diagram to find the actual argument, which happens to be \(\displaystyle {@argdp@}\) .</p>
<p>Therefore, the polar form of \(z\) is \( \displaystyle {@ta_1@}\) or \( \displaystyle {@ta1@}\)</p>

<p>2. To write \(z\) in exponential form, we need to find its modulus and argument.</p>
<p>From the previous part we know that \(\displaystyle r = |z| = {@mod@}\) and \(\theta = {@argdp@}\).</p>
<p>Therefore, the exponential form of \(z\) is \(\displaystyle {@ta2@}\)</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
